1 complaint is filed, then the parties shall stipulate to a schedule for proceedings to be established by the
2 department. The department shall, not later than 395 days after the complaint was filed, set a date for an
3 administrative hearing in the case in accordance with the stipulated schedule. After a hearing date is set, the
4 department may, in its sole discretion, issue a continuance of the hearing date only upon a showing of good
5 cause.
6 (3) (a) The hearing must be held by the department in the county where the unlawful conduct is
7 alleged to have occurred unless a party requests and is granted a change of venue for good cause shown. The
8 case in support of the complaint may be presented before the department by the charging party or an attorney
9 representing the charging party. The hearing must be held in accordance with the applicable portions of the
10 Montana Rules of Civil Procedure.
11 (b) Upon request of the hearings officer, the department may present evidence with regard to
12 activity conducted. However, the department may not represent either party in a contested case hearing.
13 (c) If the case is not settled, fully decided on order or motion, or otherwise resolved, the hearings
14 officer shall hold a hearing and issue a decision.
15 (4) All hearings conducted under this section may, upon stipulation of the parties, be heard
16 telephonically or through two-way electronic audio-video communication.
17 (5) The department or the commission may make provisions for defraying the expenses of an
18 indigent party in a hearing held pursuant to this chapter.
19 (6) The prevailing party in a hearing under this section may bring an action in district court for
20 attorney fees and costs. The court in its discretion may allow the prevailing party reasonable attorney fees and
21 costs. An action under this section must comply with the Montana Rules of Civil Procedure.
22 (7) Within 30 days after a decision in writing issued under subsection (3), a party may petition a
23 district court for judicial review of the final agency decision as provided in 2-4-702.
24
25 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Procedure on decision finding violation. (1) If the hearings officer
26 finds that a party against whom a complaint was filed has violated its policies and procedures or the policies
27 and procedures were insufficient as alleged in the complaint, the department shall order the party to refrain
28 from engaging in the violating conduct or to revise its policies and procedures. The order may:
