1 (a) prescribe conditions on the accused's license relevant to the violations and injuries found by
2 the hearings officer;
3 (b) require any reasonable measure to correct the violations and to rectify a harm, pecuniary or
4 otherwise, to the person who filed the complaint;
5 (c) require a report on the manner of compliance; or
6 (d) suspend or revoke the community home's license.
7 (2) The order may not require the payment of punitive damages.
8 (3) Whenever an order or conciliation agreement requires inspection by the department for a
9 period of time to determine whether the community home is complying with that order or agreement, the period
10 of time may not be more than 1 year.
11
12 NEW SECTION. Section 5. Enforcement of department order or conciliation agreement. If the
13 order issued under [section 4] is not obeyed, the department shall revoke the community home's license. The
14 department or a party may petition the district court in the county where the violation occurred or in which the
15 community home is located or transacts business to enforce the department's order by an appropriate order.
16 The department or a party may also commence a civil action in an appropriate district court for relief for a
17 breach of a conciliation agreement.
18
19 NEW SECTION. Section 6. Dismissal after informal proceedings -- action in district court. (1)
20 Within 90 days after the department has issued a notice of dismissal pursuant to [section 2(6)(b)], the charging
21 party may commence a civil action for appropriate relief on the merits of the case in the district court in the
22 district in which the alleged violation occurred.
23 (2) If the charging party fails to commence the civil action in the district court within 90 days after
24 the final agency decision has been issued, the claim is barred.
25 (3) The court may provide the same relief as described in [section 4]. In addition, the court may in
26 its discretion allow the prevailing party reasonable attorney fees and costs.
27
